{"cursor":"3418","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n}} was a Japanese poet and painter of the Edo period. Along with Matsuo\nBashÅ and Kobayashi Issa, Buson is considered among the greatest poets of the\nEdo Period. Buson was born in the village of Kema in Settsu Province (now Kema-\nchÅ, Miyakojima Ward in Osaka) city. His original family name was Taniguchi.\n\nAround the age of 20, Buson moved to Edo (now Tokyo) and learned poetry under\nthe tutelage of the haikai master Hayano Hajin. After Hajin died, Buson moved to\nShimÅsa Province (modern-day Ibaraki Prefecture). Following in the footsteps of\nhis idol, Matsuo BashÅ, Buson traveled through the wilds of northern HonshÅ« that\nhad been the inspiration for BashÅ's famous travel diary, [[Oku no Hosomichi]]\n(The Narrow Road to the Interior). He published his notes from the trip in 1744,\nmarking the first time he published under the name Buson.\n\nAfter traveling through various parts of Japan, including Tango (the northern\npart of modern Kyoto Prefecture) and Sanuki (Kagawa Prefecture in Shikoku),\nBuson settled down in the city of Kyoto at the age of 42. It is around this time\nthat he began to write under the name of Yosa, which he took from his mother's\nbirthplace (Yosa in the province of Tango). Henry Trubner, Tsugio Mikami,\nIdemitsu Bijutsukan. Treasures of Asian art from the Idemitsu Collection.\nSeattle Art Museum, 1981. ISBN 978-0-932216-06-9 p174\n\nBuson married at the age of 45 and had one daughter, Kuno. From this point on,\nhe remained in Kyoto, writing and teaching poetry at the Sumiya. In 1770, he\nassumed the haigÅ (ä¿³å·, haikai pen name) of Yahantei (å¤åäº­, Midnight Studio),\nwhich had been the pen name of his teacher Hajin.\n\nBuson died at the age of 68 and was buried at Konpuku-ji in Kyoto.\n","linknr":162,"url":"Yosa_Buson","recorded":1375074402,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Yosa_Buson&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Yosa_Buson&action=edit","//bits.wikimed